 planning further disturbances:\n\nThe Communists allegedly plan to incite factory strikes and then lead the workers into the streets. They believe that General Estillac Leal, commander of the central military zone, may not oppose their activities.\n\nComment: The Communists have already provoked several serious riots, including attacks on American installations, since President Vargas' suicide on 24 August. Estillac Leal, whose headquarters is in Sao Paulo, has been accused of Communist sympathies.\n\nThe Brazilian Communist Party, though outlawed, is the largest and possibly the wealthiest Communist party in Latin America. It is believed to have increased its membership nearly 50 percent in the past two years to about 110,000. Recruitment priority has been given to industrial workers, centered mainly in Sao Paulo", "token_count": 128, "token_end_0based": 127, "token_start_0based": 0, "token_text": "latin america 7 brazilian communists reported planning further disturbances the communists allegedly plan to incite factory strikes and then lead the workers into the streets they believe that general estillac leal commander of the central military zone may not oppose their activities comment the communists have already provoked several serious riots including attacks on american installations since president vargas suicide on 24 august estillac leal whose headquarters is in sao paulo has been accused of communist sympathies the brazilian communist party though outlawed is the largest and possibly the wealthiest communist party in latin america it is believed to have increased its membership nearly 50 percent in the past two years to about 110 000 recruitment priority has been given to industrial workers centered mainly in sao paulo", "unred_source_page": 7}
